So.

266
00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:05.096
That's it. huh?

267
00:13:05.120 --> 00:13:05.956
Relax.

268
00:13:05.980 --> 00:13:07.826
Don't be short with me.

269
00:13:07.850 --> 00:13:09.076
You're the writer.

270
00:13:09.100 --> 00:13:10.396
I thought it was worth a try.

271
00:13:11.370 --> 00:13:11.746
JOAN HOLLOWAY : Greta Guttman

272
00:13:11.770 --> 00:13:12.756
is here to see you.

273
00:13:12.780 --> 00:13:14.436
Send her in.

274
00:13:14.460 --> 00:13:15.336
Oh great.

275
00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:16.830
Now we get to hear from
our man in research.

276
00:13:20.700 --> 00:13:21.676
Mr. Draper.

277
00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:23.046
Mr. Romano.

278
00:13:23.070 --> 00:13:25.766
You both seem more
relaxed than I expected.

279
00:13:25.790 --> 00:13:26.866
Do you have some
kind of surprise

280
00:13:26.890 --> 00:13:28.666
for the tobacco people?

281
00:13:28.690 --> 00:13:29.856
I'm doing my own research.

282
00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:31.486
If
you're planning to continue

283
00:13:31.510 --> 00:13:32.676
with medical
testimony. you'll only

284
00:13:32.700 --> 00:13:35.446
be inviting further
government interference.

285
00:13:35.470 --> 00:13:36.946
We must police ourselves.

286
00:13:36.970 --> 00:13:37.726
There's your slogan.

287
00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:38.996
The
medical thing is dead.

288
00:13:39.020 --> 00:13:39.696
We understand that.

289
00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:40.666
Yes. dead.

290
00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:43.246
An apt choice of words.
considering the public

291
00:13:43.270 --> 00:13:45.576
is convinced that
cigarettes are poisonous.

292
00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:47.016
If we can't insist
that they're not.

293
00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:49.356
I believe my most recent surveys
have provided a solution.

294
00:13:49.380 --> 00:13:50.556
We can still suggest
that cigarettes

295
00:13:50.580 --> 00:13:52.806
are part of American life.

296
00:13:52.830 --> 00:13:54.636
Or too good to give up.

297
00:13:54.660 --> 00:13:56.946
Almost appealing. an
assertion of independence.

298
00:13:56.970 --> 00:13:59.346
So basically. if you love
danger. you'll love smoking.

299
00:13:59.370 --> 00:14:01.736
We could put a skull and
crossbones on the label.

300
00:14:01.760 --> 00:14:03.336
I love it.

301
00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:05.946
Before the
war. when I studied with Adler

302
00:14:05.970 --> 00:14:07.796
in Vienna. we postulated
that what Freud called

303
00:14:07.820 --> 00:14:10.196
the death wish is as
powerful a drive as those

304
00:14:10.220 --> 00:14:13.016
for sexual reproduction
and physical sustenance.

305
00:14:13.040 --> 00:14:14.626
Freud. you say?

306
00:14:14.650 --> 00:14:16.096
What agency is he with?

307
00:14:16.120 --> 00:14:18.256
So. we're
supposed to believe that people

308
00:14:18.280 --> 00:14:22.196
are living one way and secretly
thinking the exact opposite?

309
00:14:22.220 --> 00:14:24.136
That's ridiculous.

310
00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:25.726
Let me tell you
something. Ms. Guttman.

311
00:14:25.750 --> 00:14:27.246
Doctor.

312
00:14:27.270 --> 00:14:28.806
Dr. Guttman.

313
00:14:28.830 --> 00:14:31.896
Psychology might be great
at cocktail parties.

314
00:14:31.920 --> 00:14:34.296
but it so happens that
people were buying

315
00:14:34.320 --> 00:14:36.496
cigarettes before
Freud was born.

316
00:14:36.520 --> 00:14:38.936
The issue here isn't
why should people smoke.

317
00:14:38.960 --> 00:14:42.216
it's why should people
smoke Lucky Strike?

318
00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:45.506
Suggesting that our customers
have a... what did you call it?

319
00:14:45.530 --> 00:14:47.576
A death wish?

320
00:14:47.600 --> 00:14:49.536
I just don't see
that on a billboard.

321
00:14:49.560 --> 00:14:51.166
So what
if Reader's Digest says

322
00:14:51.190 --> 00:14:52.146
they're dangerous.

323
00:14:52.170 --> 00:14:54.846
They also said Bambi was
the book of the century.

324
00:14:54.870 --> 00:14:55.916
There's no proof.

325
00:14:55.940 --> 00:14:58.426
There's conclusive proof
that none of these low tar.

326
00:14:58.450 --> 00:15:00.896
low nicotine or
filtration systems

327
00:15:00.920 --> 00:15:03.676
have any effect on the
incidences of lung cancer.

328
00:15:03.700 --> 00:15:05.306
Just give me the damn report.

329
00:15:05.330 --> 00:15:07.356
I think you'll find
it very convincing.

330
00:15:07.380 --> 00:15:08.816
Oh. I'm sure I will.

331
00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:10.686
You're the one who found all
of our medical testimonials

332
00:15:10.710 --> 00:15:12.276
in first place.

333
00:15:12.300 --> 00:15:13.466
That's true. Mr. Draper. but...

334
00:15:13.490 --> 00:15:14.936
Has anyone else seen this?

335
00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:16.286
Of course not.
it's your account.

336
00:15:16.310 --> 00:15:17.010
Good.

337
00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:21.646
I don't want
to hear about it anymore.

338
00:15:21.670 --> 00:15:23.480
I'm sorry. I just find your
whole approach perverse.

339
00:15:26.590 --> 00:15:28.446
Good luck at the meeting.

340
00:15:28.470 --> 00:15:29.950
I'm sure it'll be a quick one.

341
00:15:36.130 --> 00:15:37.980
Sal. I'll take that drink now.

342
00:16:16.290 --> 00:16:17.090
Mr. Draper?

343
00:16:20.070 --> 00:16:22.906
Excuse me.

344
00:16:22.930 --> 00:16:24.396
Mr. Draper?

345
00:16:24.420 --> 00:16:26.790
I'm sorry to wake you. but
Mr. Campbell is outside.

346
00:16:29.690 --> 00:16:31.236
He doesn't know I'm
sleeping in here. does he?

347
00:16:31.260 --> 00:16:32.356
No. sir.

348
00:16:32.380 --> 00:16:33.080
That's good.

349
00:16:35.150 --> 00:16:36.086
Who are you?

350
00:16:36.110 --> 00:16:37.340
I'm Peggy Olson. the new girl.

351
00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:48.346
You uh... go out there
and entertain him.

352
00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:49.576
I know
it's my first day

353
00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:51.116
and I don't want to
seem uncooperative.

354
00:16:51.140 --> 00:16:55.056
but do I have to?

355
00:16:55.080 --> 00:16:57.206
I see your point.

356
00:16:57.230 --> 00:16:58.400
I brought you some aspirin.

357
00:17:03.370 --> 00:17:04.080
Send him in.

358
00:17:06.770 --> 00:17:08.376
You look like a hundred bucks.

359
00:17:08.400 --> 00:17:10.676
Ready to go sweet
talk some retail Jews?

360
00:17:10.700 --> 00:17:12.906
You are tough to take first
thing in the morning. Pete.

361
00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:14.626
I've never had any complaints.

362
00:17:14.650 --> 00:17:17.376
Speaking of which. who's
your little friend here?

363
00:17:17.400 --> 00:17:18.616
She's the new girl.

364
00:17:18.640 --> 00:17:20.486
You always get the new girl.

365
00:17:20.510 --> 00:17:23.126
Management gets all the perks.

366
00:17:23.150 --> 00:17:24.436
Where you from. honey?

367
00:17:24.460 --> 00:17:26.726
Miss Deavers
Secretarial School.

368
00:17:26.750 --> 00:17:28.376
Top notch.

369
00:17:28.400 --> 00:17:29.496
But I meant. where you from?

370
00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:32.796
Are you Amish or something?

371
00:17:32.820 --> 00:17:33.706
No.

372
00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:35.866
I'm from Brooklyn.

373
00:17:35.890 --> 00:17:37.226
Well. you're in the city now.

374
00:17:37.250 --> 00:17:38.896
It wouldn't be a sin
for us to see your legs.

375
00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:40.326
And if you pull your
waist in a little bit.

376
00:17:40.350 --> 00:17:41.736
you might look like a woman.

377
00:17:41.760 --> 00:17:43.066
Is that all Mr. Draper?

378
00:17:43.090 --> 00:17:43.766
Hey.

379
00:17:43.790 --> 00:17:45.556
I'm not done here.

380
00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:47.206
I'm working my way up.

381
00:17:47.230 --> 00:17:47.906
That'll be all.

382
00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:50.186
S Peggy. right?

383
00:17:50.210 --> 00:17:51.066
Yes.

384
00:17:51.090 --> 00:17:53.566
Oh. and it's time for
your 11 o'clock meeting.

385
00:17:53.590 --> 00:17:55.596
Oh. and sorry about
Mr. Campbell here.

386
00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:57.780
He left his manners back
at the fraternity house.

387
00:18:01.860 --> 00:18:03.846
She's a
little young for you. Draper.

388
00:18:03.870 --> 00:18:06.126
Future Mrs. Pete Campbell
is a very lucky woman.

389
00:18:06.150 --> 00:18:07.066
When's the wedding again?

390
00:18:07.090 --> 00:18:08.136
Sunday.

391
00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:09.956
Did Ken tell you about the
bachelor party tonight?

392
00:18:09.980 --> 00:18:11.176
He sure did.

393
00:18:11.200 --> 00:18:12.716
So do I get first crack at her?

394
00:18:12.740 --> 00:18:15.986
Word is she took down more
sailors than the Arizona.

395
00:18:16.010 --> 00:18:17.446
How old are you. Pete?

396
00:18:17.470 --> 00:18:18.876
I just turned 26.

397
00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:21.256
I bet the whole world looks
like one great big brassiere

398
00:18:21.280 --> 00:18:23.946
strap. just waiting
to be snapped.

399
00:18:23.970 --> 00:18:25.906
You are good with
words. Draper.

400
00:18:25.930 --> 00:18:28.086
Campell. we're both men here.
so I'm going to be direct.

401
00:18:28.110 --> 00:18:28.826
Christ.

402
00:18:28.850 --> 00:18:30.946
Are you already
sleeping with her?

403
00:18:30.970 --> 00:18:33.106
Advertising is a
very small world.

404
00:18:33.130 --> 00:18:34.486
And when you do
something like malign

405
00:18:34.510 --> 00:18:36.306
the reputation of a
girl from the Steno

406
00:18:36.330 --> 00:18:39.996
pool on her first day.
you make it even smaller.

407
00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:42.456
Keep it up. and even
if you do get my job.

408
00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:44.546
you'll never run this place.

409
00:18:44.570 --> 00:18:47.286
You'll die in that corner
office. a mid-level executive

410
00:18:47.310 --> 00:18:51.476
with a little bit of hair who
women go home with out of pity.

411
00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:54.046
Want to know why?

412
00:18:54.070 --> 00:18:55.140
Because no one will like you.

413
00:19:02.270 --> 00:19:02.946
Oh.

414
00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:05.366
Here are our
miracle workers now.

415
00:19:05.390 --> 00:19:07.296
You know Pete Campbell. of
course. your account executive.

416
00:19:07.320 --> 00:19:08.826
if you choose to do
business with us.

417
00:19:08.850 --> 00:19:10.716
And this handsome
fellow is Don Draper.

418
00:19:10.740 --> 00:19:12.596
the best creative
director in New York.

419
00:19:12.620 --> 00:19:13.996
Well. at least the building.

420
00:19:14.020 --> 00:19:15.556
Pleasure to meet you.

421
00:19:15.580 --> 00:19:16.656
Oop. sorry about that.

422
00:19:16.680 --> 00:19:18.396
I'm Rachel Menken.

423
00:19:18.420 --> 00:19:19.096
Oh.

424
00:19:19.120 --> 00:19:19.626
Uh.

425
00:19:19.650 --> 00:19:20.326
I'm sorry.

426
00:19:20.350 --> 00:19:21.586
I was expecting...

427
00:19:21.610 --> 00:19:23.606
You were expecting
me to be a man.

428
00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:26.926
My father was too.

429
00:19:26.950 --> 00:19:29.776
And you are?

430
00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:33.486
Why. Don. you remember David
Cohen. from the Art Department.

431
00:19:33.510 --> 00:19:34.526
Of course.

432
00:19:34.550 --> 00:19:35.226
David.

433
00:19:35.250 --> 00:19:38.366
One of the rising stars
here at Sterling Cooper.

434
00:19:38.390 --> 00:19:39.936
Well. why don't we make
ourselves comfortable.

435
00:19:39.960 --> 00:19:41.896
And Ms. Menken. you can tell
us what you have in mind.

436
00:19:41.920 --> 00:19:42.620
Wonderful.

437
00:19:45.450 --> 00:19:46.616
That's really subtle.

438
00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:48.296
Isn't that your shirt?

439
00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:50.540
I had to go all the way to
the mail room. but I found one.

440
00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:15.890
So. you must be Peggy Olson.

441
00:20:18.870 --> 00:20:20.116
Joan Holloway sent you over.

442
00:20:20.140 --> 00:20:20.816
She's a great girl.

443
00:20:20.840 --> 00:20:21.876
How is Joan?

444
00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:23.476
She sends her regards.

445
00:20:23.500 --> 00:20:25.046
She's a lot of fun.

446
00:20:25.070 --> 00:20:26.986
Must be a scream
to work with her.

447
00:20:27.010 --> 00:20:27.686
Yes.

448
00:20:27.710 --> 00:20:28.886
It's pretty terrific.

449
00:20:28.910 --> 00:20:29.610
Mm-hm.

450
00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:34.140
Try to make yourself
comfortable and relaxed.

451
00:20:42.600 --> 00:20:47.926
I see from your chart and your
finger that you're not married.

452
00:20:47.950 --> 00:20:49.426
That's right.

453
00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:53.316
And yet you're interested
in the contraceptive pills.

454
00:20:53.340 --> 00:20:54.476
Well...

455
00:20:54.500 --> 00:20:56.056
There's
reason to be nervous.

456
00:20:56.080 --> 00:20:58.396
Joan sent you to me because
I'm not here to judge you.

457
00:20:58.420 --> 00:20:59.526
There's nothing
wrong with a woman

458
00:20:59.550 --> 00:21:03.226
being practical about the
possibility of sexual activity.

459
00:21:03.250 --> 00:21:05.306
Spread your knees.

460
00:21:05.330 --> 00:21:06.876
That's good to hear.

461
00:21:06.900 --> 00:21:08.456
Although. as a
doctor. one would

462
00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:10.906
like to think that putting
a woman in this situation

463
00:21:10.930 --> 00:21:14.886
is not going to turn her
into some kind of strumpet.

464
00:21:14.910 --> 00:21:16.580
Slide your fanny toward
me. I'm not going to bite.

465
00:21:25.740 --> 00:21:29.236
I'll warn you now. I will
take you off this medicine

466
00:21:29.260 --> 00:21:31.256
if you abuse it.

467
00:21:31.280 --> 00:21:34.686
It's for your own good. really.

468
00:21:34.710 --> 00:21:37.806
But the fact is. even
in our modern times.

469
00:21:37.830 --> 00:21:40.690
easy women don't find husbands.

470
00:21:44.160 --> 00:21:45.706
I understand. Dr. Emerson.

471
00:21:45.730 --> 00:21:49.166
I really am a very
responsible person.

472
00:21:49.190 --> 00:21:51.746
I'm sure you're not
that kind of girl.

473
00:21:51.770 --> 00:21:54.456
Now. Joan... I'm just
kidding along here.

474
00:21:54.480 --> 00:21:55.180
You can get dressed.

475
00:21:58.750 --> 00:22:02.336
I'm going to write you a
prescription for Enovid.

476
00:22:02.360 --> 00:22:05.286
They're $11 a month. but
don't think you have to go out

477
00:22:05.310 --> 00:22:09.356
and become the town pump just
to get your money's worth.

478
00:22:09.380 --> 00:22:10.240
Excuse my French.

479
00:22:14.460 --> 00:22:15.956
So.
what Don is saying.

480
00:22:15.980 --> 00:22:17.926
is that through a variety
of media. including

481
00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:20.406
a spot during the Danny Thomas
Show. if you can afford it.

482
00:22:20.430 --> 00:22:21.976
we can really boost awareness.

483
00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:25.186
Then. a 10% off coupon
in select ladies magazines

484
00:22:25.210 --> 00:22:27.226
will increase your
first time visitors.

485
00:22:27.250 --> 00:22:32.936
Once we get them into the store.
the rest is kind of up to you.

486
00:22:32.960 --> 00:22:34.926
Mr. Draper.
our store is 60 years old.

487
00:22:34.950 --> 00:22:37.456
We share a wall with Tiffany's.

488
00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:40.606
Honestly. a coupon?

489
00:22:40.630 --> 00:22:42.886
Miss Menken. coupons work.

490
00:22:42.910 --> 00:22:44.646
I think your father would
agree with this strategy.

491
00:22:44.670 --> 00:22:45.956
He might.

492
00:22:45.980 --> 00:22:47.186
But he's not here
because we just

493
00:22:47.210 --> 00:22:50.216
had our lowest sales year ever.

494
00:22:50.240 --> 00:22:55.206
So I suppose what I think
matters most right now.

495
00:22:55.230 --> 00:22:57.286
Miss Menken. why
did you come here?

496
00:22:57.310 --> 00:23:02.626
They are a dozen other agencies
better suited to your needs.

497
00:23:02.650 --> 00:23:03.896
Well. if wanted
some man who happened

498
00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:08.126
to be for the same village as
my father to manage my account.

499
00:23:08.150 --> 00:23:10.146
I could've stayed where I was.

500
00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:12.636
Their research
favours coupons too.

501
00:23:12.660 --> 00:23:15.446
It's
not just research. Miss Menken.

502
00:23:15.470 --> 00:23:17.336
Housewives love coupons.

503
00:23:17.360 --> 00:23:19.096
I'm not interested
in housewives.

504
00:23:19.120 --> 00:23:21.146
What kind of
people do you want?

505
00:23:21.170 --> 00:23:23.676
I want your kind of
people. Mr. Draper.

506
00:23:23.700 --> 00:23:25.636
People who don't care about
coupons. whether or not they

507
00:23:25.660 --> 00:23:27.266
can afford it. people who
are coming to the store

508
00:23:27.290 --> 00:23:29.176
because it is expensive.

509
00:23:29.200 --> 00:23:32.056
But we obviously have
very different ideas.

510
00:23:32.080 --> 00:23:32.846
Yes.

511
00:23:32.870 --> 00:23:36.296
Like the customer
is always right?

512
00:23:36.320 --> 00:23:39.096
Gentlemen. I really thought
you could do better than this.

513
00:23:39.120 --> 00:23:41.886
Sterling Cooper has a
reputation for being innovative.

514
00:23:41.910 --> 00:23:43.216
Miss. you are way out of line.

515
00:23:43.240 --> 00:23:45.146
Don. please.

516
00:23:45.170 --> 00:23:46.116
Let's not get emotional here.

517
00:23:46.140 --> 00:23:47.906
There's no reason we
can't talk this out.

518
00:23:47.930 --> 00:23:48.606
Talk about what?

519
00:23:48.630 --> 00:23:50.886
This silly idea that people
are going to come to some

520
00:23:50.910 --> 00:23:53.606
store they've never been to
because it's more expensive?

521
00:23:53.630 --> 00:23:55.076
It works for Chanel.

522
00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:56.806
Menkens is not Chanel.

523
00:23:56.830 --> 00:23:58.306
That's a vote of confidence.

524
00:23:58.330 --> 00:24:00.566
What Don's saying
is... Chanel is

525
00:24:00.590 --> 00:24:02.056
a very different kind of place.

526
00:24:02.080 --> 00:24:03.176
It's French.

527
00:24:03.200 --> 00:24:04.546
It's continental.

528
00:24:04.570 --> 00:24:05.246
It's...

529
00:24:05.270 --> 00:24:07.286
Not just another
Jewish department store.

530
00:24:07.310 --> 00:24:08.686
Exactly.

531
00:24:08.710 --> 00:24:09.886
You
were right Roger.

532
00:24:09.910 --> 00:24:12.606
this place really runs on charm.

533
00:24:12.630 --> 00:24:13.636
This is ridiculous.

534
00:24:13.660 --> 00:24:14.526
Don.

535
00:24:14.550 --> 00:24:16.546
I'm not going to let a
woman talk to me like this.

536
00:24:16.570 --> 00:24:17.586
This meeting is over.

537
00:24:17.610 --> 00:24:18.380
Good luck. Miss Menken.

538
00:24:30.770 --> 00:24:31.666
Hey. Don.

539
00:24:31.690 --> 00:24:32.596
I don't blame you.

540
00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:34.226
She was way out of line.

541
00:24:34.250 --> 00:24:35.406
Adding money and
education doesn't

542
00:24:35.430 --> 00:24:36.566
take the rude edge
out of people.

543
00:24:36.590 --> 00:24:37.796
Well. Roger's not
going to be happy.

544
00:24:37.820 --> 00:24:40.896
so I guess that's good for you.

545
00:24:40.920 --> 00:24:42.496
I'm not going to pretend
I don't want your job.

546
00:24:42.520 --> 00:24:43.896
but you were right.

547
00:24:43.920 --> 00:24:46.096
I'm not great with people.

548
00:24:46.120 --> 00:24:46.796
And you are.

549
00:24:46.820 --> 00:24:49.386
I mean. not counting that
meeting we were just in.

550
00:24:49.410 --> 00:24:52.706
So. I'm kind of counting
on you to help me out.

551
00:24:52.730 --> 00:24:54.140
There's plenty of
room at the top.

552
00:24:57.410 --> 00:25:01.366
Look. I'm sorry I
was so hard on your before.

553
00:25:01.390 --> 00:25:03.766
It's just this
damn tobacco thing.

554
00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:05.416
You'll think of something.

555
00:25:05.440 --> 00:25:08.396
A man like you. I'd follow
into combat blindfolded.

556
00:25:08.420 --> 00:25:09.856
And I wouldn't be the first.

557
00:25:09.880 --> 00:25:13.026
Am I right. buddy?

558
00:25:13.050 --> 00:25:14.676
Let's take it a little slower.

559
00:25:14.700 --> 00:25:16.260
I don't want to
wake up pregnant.

560
00:25:26.040 --> 00:25:27.956
Dr. Emerson's a
dream. isn't he?

561
00:25:27.980 --> 00:25:29.796
He seemed nice.

562
00:25:29.820 --> 00:25:31.346
He has a place in Southampton.

563
00:25:31.370 --> 00:25:35.636
I'm not saying that I've
seen it. but it's beautiful.

564
00:25:35.660 --> 00:25:37.706
Now. don't be
nervous. but this is

565
00:25:37.730 --> 00:25:40.036
the nerve centre of the office.

566
00:25:40.060 --> 00:25:42.786
You and your boss rely on
the willing and cheerful

567
00:25:42.810 --> 00:25:45.506
cooperation of a few
skilled employees.

568
00:25:45.530 --> 00:25:49.916
Never snap. yell. or
be sarcastic with them.

569
00:25:49.940 --> 00:25:53.776
And above all. always
be a supplicant.

570
00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:55.066
Sterling Cooper

571
00:25:55.090 --> 00:25:58.736
how may I direct your call?

572
00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:01.196
I know you girls are busy.
but we've got a new one.

573
00:26:01.220 --> 00:26:06.156
Peggy. this is Marge.
Nannette. and Ivy.

574
00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:07.056
I brought you some things.

575
00:26:07.080 --> 00:26:10.426
I guess a sort of
getting to know you gift.

576
00:26:10.450 --> 00:26:12.436
Well. aren't you a sweetheart.

577
00:26:12.460 --> 00:26:14.436
If I know Joan. the
candy is for me.

578
00:26:14.460 --> 00:26:15.726
Joan. you're not fair.

579
00:26:15.750 --> 00:26:18.876
You know she has to lose 8
pounds by the Christmas party.

580
00:26:18.900 --> 00:26:19.996
I think you look great.

581
00:26:20.020 --> 00:26:22.166
Yeah. it's because
I'm sitting down.

582
00:26:22.190 --> 00:26:24.196
You can come back and visit
any time you want. honey.

583
00:26:24.220 --> 00:26:25.986
Who does she work for?

584
00:26:26.010 --> 00:26:27.326
Don Draper.

585
00:26:27.350 --> 00:26:28.696
They got rid of Eleanor?

586
00:26:28.720 --> 00:26:30.376
She moved on.

587
00:26:30.400 --> 00:26:31.736
Draper wasn't interested.

588
00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:33.766
Well. she couldn't
get a call through.

589
00:26:33.790 --> 00:26:35.026
Rude little thing.

590
00:26:35.050 --> 00:26:36.826
We see that
you've got your hands full.

591
00:26:36.850 --> 00:26:38.026
We don't want to be a bother.

592
00:26:38.050 --> 00:26:39.336
It's nice meeting you.

593
00:26:39.360 --> 00:26:40.816
Hey. you have great legs.

594
00:26:40.840 --> 00:26:43.756
I'd be you Mr. Draper would
like them if he could see them.

595
00:26:43.780 --> 00:26:45.356
Sterling Cooper. thank
you so much for holding.

596
00:26:45.380 --> 00:26:46.280
how may I direct your call?

597
00:26:49.340 --> 00:26:50.776
I just
don't know what

598
00:26:50.800 --> 00:26:53.526
we have to do to make these
government interlopers happy.

599
00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:55.736
They tell us to make
a safer cigarette.

600
00:26:55.760 --> 00:26:56.656
We do it.

601
00:26:56.680 --> 00:26:59.656
And then suddenly.
that's not good enough.

602
00:26:59.680 --> 00:27:02.026
Might as well be
living in Russia.

603
00:27:02.050 --> 00:27:02.750
Damn straight.

604
00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:09.856
You
know. this morning

605
00:27:09.880 --> 00:27:11.226
I got a call from
our competitors

606
00:27:11.250 --> 00:27:13.436
at Brown and
Williamson. and they're

607
00:27:13.460 --> 00:27:15.336
getting sued by the
federal government

608
00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:17.376
because of the health
claims they made.

609
00:27:17.400 --> 00:27:18.976
We're
aware of that. Mr. Garner.

610
00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:20.606
But you have to realise
that through manipulation

611
00:27:20.630 --> 00:27:23.406
of the mass media. the public
is under the impression that

612
00:27:23.430 --> 00:27:29.596
your cigarettes are linked
to certain fatal diseases.

613
00:27:29.620 --> 00:27:30.896
Manipulation
of the media...

614
00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:33.166
hell. that's what I pay you for.

615
00:27:33.190 --> 00:27:34.666
Our product is fine.

616
00:27:34.690 --> 00:27:35.986
I smoke them myself.

617
00:27:36.010 --> 00:27:37.186
My granddad smoked them.

618
00:27:37.210 --> 00:27:39.026
He died at 95-years-old.

619
00:27:39.050 --> 00:27:40.166
Was hit by a truck.

620
00:27:40.190 --> 00:27:41.136
I understand.

621
00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:42.466
But our hands are tied.

622
00:27:42.490 --> 00:27:43.666
We're no longer
allowed to advertise

623
00:27:43.690 --> 00:27:45.646
that Lucky Strikes are safe.

624
00:27:45.670 --> 00:27:46.796
So what the hell we gonna do?

625
00:27:46.820 --> 00:27:50.076
We've already funded our
own tobacco research centre

626
00:27:50.100 --> 00:27:51.786
to put this whole
rumour to rest.

627
00:27:51.810 --> 00:27:53.886
And that's a very good start.

628
00:27:53.910 --> 00:27:57.316
But it may not affect sales.

629
00:27:57.340 --> 00:27:58.910
Don. I think maybe
that's your cue.

630
00:28:01.960 --> 00:28:10.176
Well. I have been thinking
quite a bit about this.

631
00:28:10.200 --> 00:28:26.296
And uh... I mean. you know I'm a
Lucky Strike fan from way back.

632
00:28:26.320 --> 00:28:27.020
So.

633
00:28:34.750 --> 00:28:38.486
I might have a solution
At Sterling Cooper

634
00:28:38.510 --> 00:28:41.346
we've been pioneering the
burgeoning field of research.

635
00:28:41.370 --> 00:28:44.286
And our analysis shows that
the health risks associated

636
00:28:44.310 --> 00:28:47.606
with your product is not
the end of the world.

637
00:28:47.630 --> 00:28:50.506
People get in their cars
every day to go to work.

638
00:28:50.530 --> 00:28:52.606
And some of them die.

639
00:28:52.630 --> 00:28:55.046
Cars are dangerous.

640
00:28:55.070 --> 00:28:57.776
There's nothing you
can do about it.

641
00:28:57.800 --> 00:29:01.036
You still have to get
where you're going.

642
00:29:01.060 --> 00:29:03.426
Cigarettes are exactly the same.

643
00:29:03.450 --> 00:29:05.816
So why don't we
simply say. so what

644
00:29:05.840 --> 00:29:07.876
if cigarettes are dangerous?

645
00:29:07.900 --> 00:29:09.466
You're a man.

646
00:29:09.490 --> 00:29:11.526
The world is dangerous.

647
00:29:11.550 --> 00:29:13.196
Smoke your cigarette.

648
00:29:13.220 --> 00:29:17.046
You still have to get
where you're going.

649
00:29:17.070 --> 00:29:19.866
That's very interesting.

650
00:29:19.890 --> 00:29:22.766
I mean. if cigarettes
were dangerous

651
00:29:22.790 --> 00:29:24.036
it would be interesting.

652
00:29:24.060 --> 00:29:25.676
Except they aren't.

653
00:29:25.700 --> 00:29:27.326
That's your slogan?

654
00:29:27.350 --> 00:29:30.106
You're going to die
anyway. die with us?

655
00:29:30.130 --> 00:29:31.866
Actually. it's a
fairly well established

656
00:29:31.890 --> 00:29:36.946
psychological principle that
society has a death wish.

657
00:29:36.970 --> 00:29:40.396
And if we could just tap into
that. the market potential is...

658
00:29:40.420 --> 00:29:42.246
What the hell
are you talking about?

659
00:29:42.270 --> 00:29:43.756
Are you insane?

660
00:29:43.780 --> 00:29:47.026
I'm not selling rifles here.
I'm in the tobacco business.

661
00:29:47.050 --> 00:29:48.756
We're selling America.

662
00:29:48.780 --> 00:29:51.466
The Indians gave it to
us. for shit's sake.

663
00:29:51.490 --> 00:29:53.136
Come on. Dad.

664
00:29:53.160 --> 00:29:53.890
Let's get out of here.

665
00:29:56.560 --> 00:30:00.206
Bright spot is. at least we
know if we have this problem.

666
00:30:00.230 --> 00:30:01.210
everybody has this problem.

667
00:30:14.710 --> 00:30:17.466
Gentlemen. before you leave.
can I just say something?

668
00:30:17.490 --> 00:30:18.990
I don't
know Don. can you?

669
00:30:22.880 --> 00:30:25.656
The Federal Trade Commission
and Reader's Digest

670
00:30:25.680 --> 00:30:27.036
have done you a favour.

671
00:30:27.060 --> 00:30:28.846
They've let you know that
any ad that brings up

672
00:30:28.870 --> 00:30:30.736
the concept of
cigarettes and health

673
00:30:30.760 --> 00:30:36.206
together... well. it's just going
to make people think of cancer.

674
00:30:36.230 --> 00:30:39.916
Yes. and we are
grateful to them.

675
00:30:39.940 --> 00:30:44.646
But. what Lee
Jr. said is right.

676
00:30:44.670 --> 00:30:46.296
If you can't make
those health claims.

677
00:30:46.320 --> 00:30:49.286
neither can your competitors.

678
00:30:49.310 --> 00:30:51.966
So. we've got a
lot of people not

679
00:30:51.990 --> 00:30:54.806
saying anything that
sells cigarettes.

680
00:30:54.830 --> 00:30:56.726
Not exactly.

681
00:30:56.750 --> 00:30:59.186
This is the greatest
advertising opportunity

682
00:30:59.210 --> 00:31:01.746
since the invention of cereal.

683
00:31:01.770 --> 00:31:06.976
We have six identical companies
making six identical products.

684
00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.346
We can say anything we want.

685
00:31:09.370 --> 00:31:11.776
How do you make your cigarettes?

686
00:31:11.800 --> 00:31:13.676
I don't know.

687
00:31:13.700 --> 00:31:16.166
Shame on you.

688
00:31:16.190 --> 00:31:18.646
We breed insect
repellent tobacco seeds.

689
00:31:18.670 --> 00:31:20.856
plant them in the North
Carolina sunshine.

690
00:31:20.880 --> 00:31:24.086
grow it. cut it.
cure it. toast it...

691
00:31:24.110 --> 00:31:25.186
There you go.

692
00:31:25.210 --> 00:31:25.910
There you go.

693
00:31:34.700 --> 00:31:36.286
But everybody else's
tobacco is toasted.

694
00:31:36.310 --> 00:31:36.986
No.

695
00:31:37.010 --> 00:31:41.136
Everybody else's
tobacco is poisonous.

696
00:31:41.160 --> 00:31:43.400
Lucky Strikes is toasted.

697
00:31:46.250 --> 00:31:47.326
Well. gentlemen.
I don't think I

698
00:31:47.350 --> 00:31:51.096
have to tell you what
you just witnessed here.

699
00:31:51.120 --> 00:31:51.870
I think you do.

700
00:31:54.530 --> 00:31:59.866
Advertising is based on
one thing... happiness.

701
00:31:59.890 --> 00:32:02.236
And you know what happiness is?

702
00:32:02.260 --> 00:32:06.606
Happiness is the
smell of a new car.

703
00:32:06.630 --> 00:32:08.736
It's freedom from fear.

704
00:32:08.760 --> 00:32:12.446
It's a billboard on the side
of the road that screams

705
00:32:12.470 --> 00:32:16.550
with reassurance that
whatever you're doing is OK.

706
00:32:20.650 --> 00:32:21.570
You are OK.

707
00:32:30.210 --> 00:32:30.910
It's toasted.

708
00:32:34.940 --> 00:32:35.830
I get it.

709
00:32:47.150 --> 00:32:49.166
You had me worried.

710
00:32:49.190 --> 00:32:52.566
I don't know if you
were drunk or not drunk.

711
00:32:52.590 --> 00:32:54.106
But that was inspired.

712
00:32:54.130 --> 00:32:56.466
For the record. pulled
it out of thin air.

713
00:32:56.490 --> 00:32:58.036
So. thank you up there.

714
00:32:58.060 --> 00:33:00.636
You're looking
in the wrong direction.

715
00:33:00.660 --> 00:33:03.196
So now that I've got you
in the afterglow here.

716
00:33:03.220 --> 00:33:06.776
what do you say you reconsider
this presidential campaign?

717
00:33:06.800 --> 00:33:09.026
I don't know.
bunting and babies?

718
00:33:09.050 --> 00:33:10.816
That's hard work.

719
00:33:10.840 --> 00:33:12.146
I don't want to
make a hash of it.

720
00:33:12.170 --> 00:33:12.846
Modesty.

721
00:33:12.870 --> 00:33:14.466
That's adorable.

722
00:33:14.490 --> 00:33:15.286
Consider the product.

723
00:33:15.310 --> 00:33:17.166
He's young. handsome. Navy hero.

724
00:33:17.190 --> 00:33:19.036
Honestly. it shouldn't be
too difficult to convince

725
00:33:19.060 --> 00:33:20.796
America Dick Nixon is a winner.

726
00:33:21.770 --> 00:33:24.586
Mr.
Draper. you've got visitors.

727
00:33:24.610 --> 00:33:28.046
Could you be a little
more specific. honey?

728
00:33:28.070 --> 00:33:30.566
We heard you saved the day.

729
00:33:30.590 --> 00:33:31.756
Thank you. boys.

730
00:33:31.780 --> 00:33:33.416
I appreciate it.

731
00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:34.756
I told them how
amazing you were.

732
00:33:34.780 --> 00:33:36.606
I'm still tingling.

733
00:33:36.630 --> 00:33:37.836
Well. it looks like
you're all going

734
00:33:37.860 --> 00:33:39.766
to engage in a little
mid-level camaraderie.

735
00:33:39.790 --> 00:33:40.966
so I'll be on my way.

736
00:33:40.990 --> 00:33:42.286
Don. thanks again
for the home run.

737
00:33:42.310 --> 00:33:43.226
I love to come through.

738
00:33:43.250 --> 00:33:44.556
Speaking of which.
any chance you could

739
00:33:44.580 --> 00:33:46.276
patch things up
with Rachel Menken?

740
00:33:46.300 --> 00:33:48.976
Anyway you can be as
charming as I said you were?

741
00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:51.466
Haven't you had enough
of my magic for one day?

742
00:33:51.490 --> 00:33:53.566
She's worth $3 million.

743
00:33:53.590 --> 00:33:54.290
You're a whore.

744
00:33:57.790 --> 00:33:59.326
Peggy.

745
00:33:59.350 --> 00:34:00.666
Can she get us a
little more ice?

746
00:34:00.690 --> 00:34:02.096
Yes. Mr. Draper.

747
00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:03.446
Just a minute.

748
00:34:03.470 --> 00:34:04.616
Fellas. I think
this party is going

749
00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:05.756
to have to move elsewhere.

750
00:34:05.780 --> 00:34:07.026
Well. move wherever you want.

751
00:34:07.050 --> 00:34:08.116
But it's 5:15.

752
00:34:08.140 --> 00:34:10.016
The bachelor party is under way.

753
00:34:10.040 --> 00:34:11.226
I don't know.

754
00:34:11.250 --> 00:34:12.116
Oh. come on Don.

755
00:34:12.140 --> 00:34:13.096
All hands on deck.

756
00:34:13.120 --> 00:34:15.526
Aren't you going to help us
give Pete his big send off?

757
00:34:15.550 --> 00:34:16.250
Maybe next time.

758
00:34:19.830 --> 00:34:20.716
Come on guys.

759
00:34:20.740 --> 00:34:21.486
Don will join us later.

760
00:34:21.510 --> 00:34:22.210
Right Don?

761
00:34:30.340 --> 00:34:34.946
If Greta's research was any
good. I would have used it.

762
00:34:34.970 --> 00:34:36.496
What are you talking about?

763
00:34:36.520 --> 00:34:39.036
I'm saying I
had a report just like that.

764
00:34:39.060 --> 00:34:41.376
And it's not like there's
some magic machine that

765
00:34:41.400 --> 00:34:45.246
makes identical
copies of things.

766
00:34:45.270 --> 00:34:46.410
I still think she was right.

767
00:34:52.490 --> 00:34:54.626
Have a great night. Pete.

768
00:34:54.650 --> 00:34:55.350
Congratulations.

769
00:35:05.570 --> 00:35:08.426
I heard you were
amazing in the meeting.

770
00:35:08.450 --> 00:35:09.540
Fear stimulates my imagination.

771
00:35:12.880 --> 00:35:17.036
I just wanted to thank
you for a great first day.

772
00:35:17.060 --> 00:35:22.190
And for... you know. standing
up for me with Mr. Campbell.

773
00:35:37.060 --> 00:35:39.710
First of all. Peggy. I'm
your boss. not your boyfriend.

774
00:35:42.680 --> 00:35:44.976
Second of all. you ever let Pete
Campbell go through my trash

775
00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:46.176
again. and you won't
be able to find

776
00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:48.130
a job selling sandwiches
in Penn Station.

777
00:35:51.380 --> 00:35:54.216
He said he left his
fountain pen in here.

778
00:35:54.240 --> 00:35:54.940
I didn't know.

779
00:35:59.460 --> 00:36:02.356
I hope you don't think
I'm the kind of girl...

780
00:36:02.380 --> 00:36:05.466
Of course not.

781
00:36:05.490 --> 00:36:06.396
Go home.

782
00:36:06.420 --> 00:36:07.796
Put your curlers in.

783
00:36:07.820 --> 00:36:08.920
We'll get a fresh
start tomorrow.

784
00:36:11.490 --> 00:36:12.246
Oh.

785
00:36:12.270 --> 00:36:14.730
And Peggy... I need
you to place a call.

786
00:36:36.780 --> 00:36:39.846
I want to see you here every 15
minutes whether you have drinks

787
00:36:39.870 --> 00:36:40.996
or not.

788
00:36:41.020 --> 00:36:44.166
Every five minutes.

789
00:36:44.190 --> 00:36:46.346
Let's live here.

790
00:36:46.370 --> 00:36:48.166
look tonight.

791
00:36:48.190 --> 00:36:49.826
You have a
girlfriend. Salvatore?

792
00:36:49.850 --> 00:36:50.566
Come on.

793
00:36:50.590 --> 00:36:52.966
I'm Italian.

794
00:36:52.990 --> 00:36:54.120
Is there some
kind of party here?

795
00:36:56.970 --> 00:36:58.316
How did you swing it?

796
00:36:58.340 --> 00:36:59.726
They work at the automat.

797
00:36:59.750 --> 00:37:02.696
He pressed a button
and they came out.

798
00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:04.396
I hope we're not
interrupting anything.

799
00:37:04.420 --> 00:37:05.646
Definitely not.

800
00:37:05.670 --> 00:37:07.006
Well. I have the best seat.

801
00:37:07.030 --> 00:37:08.266
What are we drinking?

802
00:37:08.290 --> 00:37:10.546
More of whatever is
making you the way you are.

803
00:37:10.570 --> 00:37:12.376
I love this place.

804
00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:15.476
It's hot. loud. and
filled with men.

805
00:37:15.500 --> 00:37:16.310
I know what you mean.

806
00:37:29.100 --> 00:37:31.966
Oh my God. I can
already feel it.

807
00:37:31.990 --> 00:37:34.486
I have a feeling you're
like this all the time.

808
00:37:34.510 --> 00:37:35.686
I like to laugh.

809
00:37:35.710 --> 00:37:36.586
Is that right?

810
00:37:36.610 --> 00:37:39.276
Now you stop that.

811
00:37:39.300 --> 00:37:41.556
You said you liked to laugh.

812
00:37:41.580 --> 00:37:42.776
I mean it.

813
00:37:42.800 --> 00:37:44.106
It's too...

814
00:37:44.130 --> 00:37:45.796
Too delicious?

815
00:37:45.820 --> 00:37:47.776
Hey.
I said stop it.

816
00:37:47.800 --> 00:37:49.266
What do you think you're doing?

817
00:37:49.290 --> 00:37:50.546
You know exactly.

818
00:37:50.570 --> 00:37:51.246
Um.

819
00:37:51.270 --> 00:37:52.236
You know what girls?

820
00:37:52.260 --> 00:37:53.716
I think we should go.

821
00:37:53.740 --> 00:37:54.706
Oh come on.

822
00:37:54.730 --> 00:37:55.720
You're hurting me.

823
00:37:58.690 --> 00:38:01.946
I'll be good.

824
00:38:01.970 --> 00:38:03.430
Buy the girls
whatever they want.

825
00:38:10.730 --> 00:38:12.986
So. what do you fellows do?

826
00:38:13.010 --> 00:38:15.686
You're looking at the
finest ad men in New York.

827
00:38:15.710 --> 00:38:16.760
Hell. the world.

828
00:38:42.490 --> 00:38:44.806
The lady. a special Mai Tai.

829
00:38:44.830 --> 00:38:46.530
And one whiskey neat.

830
00:38:51.450 --> 00:38:53.666
So.

831
00:38:53.690 --> 00:38:55.766
You're going to
ply me with drinks

832
00:38:55.790 --> 00:38:59.506
and convince me what a
terrible mistake I'm making.

833
00:38:59.530 --> 00:39:01.306
That is quite a drink.

834
00:39:01.330 --> 00:39:02.930
You got in trouble. didn't you?

835
00:39:07.080 --> 00:39:08.356
I shouldn't have
lost my temper.

836
00:39:08.380 --> 00:39:10.706
And I certainly shouldn't
have treated you

837
00:39:10.730 --> 00:39:12.056
like anything less
than a client.

838
00:39:12.080 --> 00:39:12.780
Apology accepted.

839
00:39:15.490 --> 00:39:17.526
So you understand.

840
00:39:17.550 --> 00:39:19.746
Now I do.

841
00:39:19.770 --> 00:39:23.756
It was refreshing. really.

842
00:39:23.780 --> 00:39:25.286
I mean. actually
hearing all the things

843
00:39:25.310 --> 00:39:27.220
I always assumed
people were thinking.

844
00:39:30.090 --> 00:39:31.460
Well. I'm not really
as bad as all that.

845
00:39:34.740 --> 00:39:36.346
I was under a lot of pressure.

846
00:39:36.370 --> 00:39:37.070
Another account.

847
00:39:40.870 --> 00:39:43.216
Doesn't really matter.

848
00:39:43.240 --> 00:39:43.940
No. it doesn't.

849
00:39:49.570 --> 00:39:51.376
So. without making
things worse.

850
00:39:51.400 --> 00:39:52.876
can I ask you a
personal question?

851
00:39:52.900 --> 00:39:56.146
Don't you want to get a
second drink in me first?

852
00:39:56.170 --> 00:39:56.970
Why aren't you married?

853
00:39:59.650 --> 00:40:01.676
Are you asking
what's wrong with me?

854
00:40:01.700 --> 00:40:03.836
It's just that you're a
beautiful. educated woman.

855
00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:05.956
Don't you think that getting
married and having a family

856
00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:07.746
would make you happier
than all the headaches

857
00:40:07.770 --> 00:40:10.370
that go along with
fighting people like me?

858
00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:15.456
If I weren't a
woman. I would be

859
00:40:15.480 --> 00:40:18.836
allowed to ask you
the same question.

860
00:40:18.860 --> 00:40:20.196
And if I weren't a
woman. I wouldn't

861
00:40:20.220 --> 00:40:24.666
have to choose between putting
on an apron and the thrill

862
00:40:24.690 --> 00:40:27.836
of making my father's store what
I always thought it should be.

863
00:40:27.860 --> 00:40:28.536
So that's it.

864
00:40:28.560 --> 00:40:31.836
You won't get
married because you

865
00:40:31.860 --> 00:40:34.946
find business to be a thrill?

866
00:40:34.970 --> 00:40:35.916
That.

867
00:40:35.940 --> 00:40:42.126
And I've never been in love.

868
00:40:42.150 --> 00:40:45.216
She won't get married because
she's never been in love.

869
00:40:45.240 --> 00:40:46.196
I think I wrote that.

870
00:40:46.220 --> 00:40:48.006
Used to sell nylons.

871
00:40:48.030 --> 00:40:52.606
For a lot of people.
love isn't just a slogan.

872
00:40:52.630 --> 00:40:53.576
Oh. you mean love.

873
00:40:53.600 --> 00:40:56.426
You mean. big lightning bolt to
the heart where you can't eat

874
00:40:56.450 --> 00:40:57.376
and you can't work.

875
00:40:57.400 --> 00:41:01.590
And you just run off and
get married and make babies.

876
00:41:04.260 --> 00:41:07.976
The reason you haven't felt it
is because it doesn't exist.

877
00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:13.926
What you call love was invented
by guys like me to sell nylons.

878
00:41:13.950 --> 00:41:16.326
Is that right?

879
00:41:16.350 --> 00:41:19.536
Pretty sure about it.

880
00:41:19.560 --> 00:41:21.166
You're born alone
and you die alone

881
00:41:21.190 --> 00:41:23.656
and this world just drops a
bunch of rules on top of you

882
00:41:23.680 --> 00:41:24.996
to make you forget those facts.

883
00:41:25.020 --> 00:41:28.496
But I've never forget.

884
00:41:28.520 --> 00:41:31.666
I'm living like
there's no tomorrow.

885
00:41:31.690 --> 00:41:35.406
Because there isn't one.

886
00:41:35.430 --> 00:41:39.606
I don't think I realised
it until this moment...

887
00:41:39.630 --> 00:41:45.886
but it must be hard
being a man too.

888
00:41:45.910 --> 00:41:48.766
Excuse me?

889
00:41:48.790 --> 00:41:49.466
Mr. Draper...

890
00:41:49.490 --> 00:41:50.386
Don.

891
00:41:50.410 --> 00:41:51.536
Mr. Draper.

892
00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:54.676
I don't know what it is
you really believe in.

893
00:41:54.700 --> 00:41:59.046
But I do know what it feels
like to be out of place.

894
00:41:59.070 --> 00:42:01.826
To be disconnected.

895
00:42:01.850 --> 00:42:04.786
To see the whole world laid
out in front of you the way

896
00:42:04.810 --> 00:42:07.516
other people live it.

897
00:42:07.540 --> 00:42:11.020
There's something about you
that tells me you know it too.

898
00:42:17.880 --> 00:42:18.850
I don't know if that's true.

899
00:42:21.540 --> 00:42:24.906
You want another drink?

900
00:42:24.930 --> 00:42:26.376
No.

901
00:42:26.400 --> 00:42:28.520
But you can tell your
boss that you charmed me.

902
00:42:36.240 --> 00:42:38.726
So I guess we'll be
seeing each other again.

903
00:42:38.750 --> 00:42:39.926
I'll be back in
the office Monday

904
00:42:39.950 --> 00:42:44.326
morning for a real meeting.

905
00:42:44.350 --> 00:42:45.350
I'd like that.

906
00:43:01.810 --> 00:43:03.226
We're not buying anything.

907
00:43:03.250 --> 00:43:05.756
Actually... for the
first time today.

908
00:43:05.780 --> 00:43:08.426
I'm not selling anything.

909
00:43:08.450 --> 00:43:10.286
Does Peggy live here?

910
00:43:10.310 --> 00:43:11.010
Hold on.

911
00:43:23.590 --> 00:43:24.460
Do you know him?

912
00:43:27.410 --> 00:43:30.386
It's OK. Marjorie.
we work together.

913
00:43:30.410 --> 00:43:32.096
He's really drunk.

914
00:43:32.120 --> 00:43:33.090
It's OK. Marjorie.

915
00:43:36.420 --> 00:43:37.866
So.

916
00:43:37.890 --> 00:43:38.590
What are you doing.

917
00:43:41.060 --> 00:43:41.736
Nothing.

918
00:43:41.760 --> 00:43:44.956
Just sitting in my room
listening to records.

919
00:43:44.980 --> 00:43:47.346
I'm getting married on Sunday.

920
00:43:47.370 --> 00:43:48.070
I heard that.

921
00:43:51.660 --> 00:43:52.820
You must think I'm a creep.

922
00:43:56.330 --> 00:43:57.070
Why are you here?

923
00:44:07.890 --> 00:44:09.190
I wanted to see you tonight.

924
00:44:14.770 --> 00:44:16.686
Me?

925
00:44:16.710 --> 00:44:17.670
I had to see you.

926
00:44:28.330 --> 00:44:29.566
Marjorie?

927
00:44:29.590 --> 00:44:31.786
Yeah. Peg?

928
00:44:31.810 --> 00:44:32.540
I'm going to bed now.

929
00:45:59.820 --> 00:46:01.466
I called the office.

930
00:46:01.490 --> 00:46:02.540
They said you'd left.

931
00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:09.446
I didn't want to bother you.

932
00:46:09.470 --> 00:46:10.436
It's no bother.

933
00:46:10.460 --> 00:46:13.150
I just assumed you were
staying in the city again.

934
00:46:16.130 --> 00:46:18.120
There's a plate in the oven.

935
00:46:24.100 --> 00:46:26.076
Unless you're not hungry.

936
00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:26.800
I'm not.

937
00:46:31.940 --> 00:46:33.916
I'll be right back.

938
00:46:33.940 --> 00:46:34.940
Don't move.
